"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522972","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-13","<p>The Civil Service is committed to becoming representative of the modern Britain it serves and our aim is to be the most inclusive employer in the UK. This ambition is set out in our Talent Action Plan, refreshed in March 2016. This plan commits the Civil Service to actions that aim to remove barriers to success faced by underrepresented groups. All government departments are committed to the delivery of this plan. Permanent Secretaries have clear accountability for the diversity agenda and progress within their departments is measured through their personal diversity objectives. The plan is being delivered as part of the wider Civil Service Workforce Strategy.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-06-13T06:42:02.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522972/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522972/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522972/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-06","Civil Servants: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what discussions he has had with Cabinet colleagues on his Department's plans to diversify the civil service.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","39321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522973","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-10","<p>The Bridge Group Report into Socio-Economic Diversity in the Fast Stream recommended that the Fast Stream should introduce at least one regional assessment centre from Autumn 2016 and move to a greater number of regional assessment centres in future years.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-06-10T13:23:59.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522973/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522973/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522973/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-06","Civil Servants: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what progress the Government has made on implementing its policy to move graduate recruitment outside London and establish a regional assessment centre.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","39302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522974","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-06-09","<p>The Ministerial and other Pensions and Salaries Act 1991 (Section 4 of Chapter 5) governs Ministerial severance payments. The legislation outlines the criteria upon which severance payments are made and how the amount is calculated.</p><p> </p><p>The relevant section of the legislation can be found at: <a href="http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1991/5/section/4" target="_blank">http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1991/5/section/4</a></p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-06-09T12:32:57.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522974/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522974/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522974/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-06-06","Department for Work and Pensions: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether the right hon. Member for Chingford and Woodford Green received a severance package following his resignation from the post of Secretary of State for Work and Pensions.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","39306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522975","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-14","<p>The EU referendum will be overseen by the Chief Counting Officer, chair of the independent Electoral Commission, who is responsible for making sure the referendum is held in accordance with the legislation governing the conduct of the poll. The Electoral Commission has recently issued a statement setting out the actions that have been taken to address an issue with elections software used by a number of local authorities in England and Wales. They will ensure that any postal votes which have been issued to electors who are not eligible to vote in the referendum will be cancelled and none of these electors will be shown as eligable on the electoral register to be used at polling stations on the 23rd June.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-06-14T16:10:58.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522975/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522975/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522975/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-06","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps he is taking to ensure that people who are not eligible to vote in the EU referendum and who have received ballot papers in error are not able to use those ballot papers.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","39294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522976","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-13","<p>Before the purdah period began, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) supported the Electoral Commission's global campaign to encourage eligible British citizens living abroad to register to vote, using its network of posts to reach British nationals around the world.</p><p>The Government has made its position on the UK’s membership of the EU clear. It has published a number of papers analysing the choice facing the British people. These were made available on Gov.UK.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-06-13T13:14:15.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522976/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522976/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522976/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-06","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what information the Government has provided to British citizens living abroad who are eligible to vote in the EU referendum on that referendum.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","39295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522977","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-09","<p>The Office for Budget Responsibility (OBR) revised the forecast for Marriage Allowance at Budget 2016. Details were published in the OBR’s Economic and Fiscal Outlook in March 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The Government remains committed to recognising marriage through the tax system. Marriage Allowance could benefit eligible couples by up to £432 this year if couples also backdate their claim to 2015-16. HM Revenue and Customs is continuing to look at ways to increase take-up of Marriage Allowance, including through further advertising, to ensure all eligible couples are able to take advantage of the allowance.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","39337","2016-06-09T14:42:51.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522977/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522977/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522977/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-06","Married People: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much was allocated to the married couples tax allowance in 2015-16; and how much was spent on that allowance in that year.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","39336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522978","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-09","<p>The Office for Budget Responsibility (OBR) revised the forecast for Marriage Allowance at Budget 2016. Details were published in the OBR’s Economic and Fiscal Outlook in March 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The Government remains committed to recognising marriage through the tax system. Marriage Allowance could benefit eligible couples by up to £432 this year if couples also backdate their claim to 2015-16. HM Revenue and Customs is continuing to look at ways to increase take-up of Marriage Allowance, including through further advertising, to ensure all eligible couples are able to take advantage of the allowance.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","39336","2016-06-09T14:42:51.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522978/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522978/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522978/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-06","Married People: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much has been allocated in the current financial year to the married couples tax allowance; and how much he expects the Government to spend on that allowance in this financial year.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","39337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522979","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-09","<p>The UK responds positively to requests from developing countries for renegotiation of tax treaties.</p><p> </p><p>The UK recognises that treaty partners may now want higher levels of source taxation than are contained in treaties negotiated many years ago. However, the eventual level of source state taxation in a renegotiated treaty reflects the balance of the agreed priorities.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","39345","2016-06-09T14:43:50.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522979/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522979/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522979/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-06","Taxation: Treaties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what his Department's policy is on requests from taxation treaty partners for changes to the levels of source taxation in such treaties.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","39346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522980","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-09","<p>The UK responds positively to requests from developing countries for renegotiation of tax treaties.</p><p> </p><p>The UK recognises that treaty partners may now want higher levels of source taxation than are contained in treaties negotiated many years ago. However, the eventual level of source state taxation in a renegotiated treaty reflects the balance of the agreed priorities.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","39346","2016-06-09T14:43:50.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522980/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522980/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522980/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-06","Taxation: Developing Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what his Department's policy is on requests from developing countries with whom the UK has taxation treaties to renegotiate the terms of such treaties.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","39345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522981","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-14","<p>The Government is clear that consumers must be able to access clear and transparent information about the charges that may apply to financial services products, including bank accounts. In addition, the Financial Conduct Authority requires firms to be clear, fair and not misleading when giving information to consumers, including on fees and charges.</p><p> </p><p>Following extensive Government negotiations with the banking industry on basic bank accounts, in January 2016 the UK’s nine largest banks and building societies implemented an agreement to end bank charges on those accounts when a direct debit or standing order fails. Basic bank accounts are now truly fee-free, helping people to manage their money without fear of running up an overdraft.</p><p> </p><p>The Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) is currently investigating the retail banking market, including personal current accounts. In its May 2016 provisional decision on remedies, the CMA proposed requiring banks to take steps including: a monthly maximum charge for unarranged overdrafts; alerts to help customers avoid unarranged overdraft charges; improving comparisons by allowing customers to share data on transactions with other banks and trusted third parties; and regular prompts for customers to check that they are getting good value from their banking provider. The CMA will publish its final report on the retail banking market investigation by 12 August 2016. The Government stands ready to take action once the final report is published.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-06-14T09:15:23.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522981/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522981/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522981/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-06","Bank Services: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he has taken to regulate the level of bank account charges in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","39461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522982","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-14","<p>As part of the government’s transparency agenda, the department publishes on a monthly basis, information on payroll and non-payroll staff. The link for the requested years can be found below:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/workforce-management--2?1" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/workforce-management--2?1</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There are no civil servants contracted to the department who are paid through public limited companies.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","39391 ; 39407","2016-06-14T10:25:33.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522982/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522982/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522982/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-06","Treasury: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much was spent on non-payroll staff in his Department in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","39478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522983","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-14","<p>As part of the government’s transparency agenda, the department publishes on a monthly basis, information on payroll and non-payroll staff. The link for the requested years can be found below:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/workforce-management--2?1" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/workforce-management--2?1</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There are no civil servants contracted to the department who are paid through public limited companies.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","39407 ; 39478","2016-06-14T10:25:33.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522983/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522983/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522983/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-06","Treasury: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what proportion of staff in his Department were (a) payroll and (b) non-payroll staff in each financial year from 2010-11 to 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","39391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522984","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-14","<p>As part of the government’s transparency agenda, the department publishes on a monthly basis, information on payroll and non-payroll staff. The link for the requested years can be found below:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/workforce-management--2?1" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/workforce-management--2?1</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There are no civil servants contracted to the department who are paid through public limited companies.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","39391 ; 39478","2016-06-14T10:25:33.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522984/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522984/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522984/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-06","Treasury: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many civil servants in his Department are paid through limited companies.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","39407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522985","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-14","<p>Economic development in Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales is the responsibility of the devolved administrations. At the 2015 Spending Review, the government announced that funding available for infrastructure investment via the block grant would rise by 12% in Northern Ireland, 14% in Scotland and 17% in Wales through to 2020-21. At Budget 2016 the government then committed an additional £220m of funding through the Barnett Formula to Northern Ireland, over £650m to Scotland, and more than £380m to Wales.</p><p> </p><p>The government is also empowering England to take responsibility for economic growth. By May 2017, over half the population of the North of England will have a powerful new directly elected mayor. £200m has been committed to Transport for the North, strategic investments have been made in science (including £235m for the Sir Henry Royce Institute,) and Hull has been backed as the 2017 City of Culture. The government is investing in growth in all parts of the country, for example through creating a Midlands Engine Investment Fund of over £250m. Meanwhile our business rate reforms offer local authorities across England unprecedented new levers to drive growth.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-06-14T09:13:53.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522985/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522985/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522985/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-06","Economic Growth","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that every region in the UK benefits from future economic growth.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","39428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522986","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-14","<p>My Department spent the following amounts on non-payroll staff in 2015-16, as will be reported in our Annual Report and Accounts:</p><p>Cost of contingent labour (agency staff and contractors) - £2,858,046</p><p>Cost of consultants/consultancy - £511,460</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2016-06-14T14:48:44.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522986/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522986/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522986/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-06","Department for Communities and Local Government: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much was spent on non-payroll staff in his Department in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","39464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522987","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-14","<p>No civil servants in my Department are paid through limited companies.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2016-06-14T14:51:48.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522987/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522987/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522987/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-06","Department for Communities and Local Government: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many civil servants in his Department are paid through limited companies.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","39395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522988","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-14","<p>Details of payroll and non-payroll staffing in my Department are published on Gov.uk and in the Annual Report and Accounts.</p><p> </p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2016-06-14T14:47:55.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522988/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522988/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522988/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-06","Department for Communities and Local Government: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of staff in his Department were (a) payroll and (b) non-payroll staff in each financial year from 2010-11 to 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","39377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522989","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-06-10","<p>Defra and the Department for Communities and Local Government are working on the Litter Strategy for England to improve the way we all tackle the scourge of litter. We have an ambitious goal, to substantially reduce litter and littering in England, ensuring that our communities, natural landscape, roads and highways are clean and pleasant.</p><p> </p><p>The Strategy will focus on three key themes: education and awareness; punishing offenders; and better cleansing and litter infrastructure. These will be backed up by specific actions under each objective.</p><p> </p><p>We have established a Litter Strategy Advisory Group. We held a Litter Forum earlier this year to gather stakeholder views for the Strategy’s content and have begun working with a wide range of stakeholders to develop our approach. We will publish the Strategy this year and a great deal of work will be taken forward in the coming months.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-06-10T12:22:11.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522989/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522989/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522989/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-06-06","Litter","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what progress has been made on the National Litter Strategy which was announced on 5 December 2015.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","39439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522990","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-14","<p>No separate annual record of locations visited by Ministers and officials is kept by this department. However, details of Ministers meetings with external organisations are published online as part of our transparency agenda. Details can be found at:</p><p>http://www.gov.uk/government/publications?departments%5B%5D=department-for-communities-and-local-government&amp;publication type=transparency-data</p><p> </p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2016-06-14T14:51:23.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522990/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522990/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522990/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-06","Department for Communities and Local Government: Domestic Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 2 June 2016 to Question 38323, whether an annual record is kept by his Department of locations visited by Ministers and officials of his Department; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","39438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522991","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-09","<p>A range of officials from across Government will work to support the West Midlands Combined Authority in the delivery of their policy outcomes. Civil Servants from my Department, including those based in Birmingham, and from the Homes and Communities Agency, will support the authorities of the West Midlands on a number of key local delivery priorities, including on planning, housing, and programmes to drive local economic growth, such as Enterprise Zones and European funding.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2016-06-09T15:14:14.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522991/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522991/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522991/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-06","West Midlands Combined Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate his Department has made of how many full-time equivalent civil servants will support the West Midlands Combined Authority in each of the next five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","39484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522992","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-09","<p>My Department has a number of staff who are already based in the West Midlands, who have worked closely - and who will continue to work closely - with the authorities of the West Midlands on the development and implementation of their devolution agreement and who support delivery of key growth programmes such as Enterprise Zones and European funding.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-06-09T15:15:02.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522992/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522992/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522992/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-06","West Midlands Combined Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether his Department plans to relocate Civil Service staff from London to the West Midlands to support the West Midlands Combined Authority Deal; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","39486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522993","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-14","I refer the Honourable member to my response to PQ 39132, answered on the 9th June.","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-06-14T10:47:18.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522993/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522993/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522993/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-06","Culture: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that legacy funding from the Government for the Great Exhibition of the North is spent effectively.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","39354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522994","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-13","<p>Government is committed to increasing physical activity as set out in our sport strategy, ‘Sporting Future: A New Strategy for an Active Nation’ published late last year. That strategy removed the artificial barriers between sport and wider physical activity, broadening Sport England’s remit to include cycling, dancing and walking. The recently published Sport England strategy, ‘Towards an Active Nation’, sets out their plans to implement this new approach.</p><p> </p><p>I recognise that creating a more active society will require action by a range of bodies working together over a significant period of time. I therefore welcome the work of Legacy Park Ltd in Sheffield in bringing together partners across local government, the health sector, academia, elite and community sport and the private sector. I look forward to seeing their ambitious plans to establish sport facilities for elite and community use and an Advanced Wellbeing Research Centre that would work with the National Centre for Sport and Exercise Medicine to provide health and wellbeing research and learning.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett",,"2016-06-13T13:59:47.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522994/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522994/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522994/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-06","Exercise and Sports: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent assessment the Government has made of the contribution of the work of the Olympic Legacy Park in Sheffield to breaking down distinctions between sport and wider physical activity.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","39320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522995","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-09","<p>The July 2015 budget announced an average 1% pay award for public sector workforces from 2016/17. This is set out in Civil Service Pay Guidance, which is issued each year following negotiation with the Trade Unions.</p><p>Pay restraint is one of the many difficult choices the Government has had to make to put the public finances back on track and makes a significant contribution to protecting jobs and maintaining public services.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-06-09T12:24:28.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522995/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522995/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522995/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-06","Information Commissioner: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the one per cent rise from 2016-17 on the (a) wage levels in real terms, (b) living standards and (c) disposable income of workers in the Information Commissioner's Office to the end of this Parliament.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","39308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522996","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-14","<p>The published Cabinet Office Annual Report and Accounts (ARA) contains both the proportion of staff in the Department for Culture, Media and Sport that are (a) payroll and (b) non-payroll staff and the associated spend. The ARA for each financial year from 2010-11 to 2014-15 are available on <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">gov.uk</a>.</p><p>The 2015-16 data will be published in due course.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","39465","2016-06-14T15:09:24.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522996/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522996/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522996/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-06","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of staff in his Department were (a) payroll and (b) non-payroll staff in each financial year from 2010-11 to 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","39378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522997","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-14","<p>There are no Civil Servants in DCMS paid through limited companies.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-06-14T15:10:01.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522997/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522997/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522997/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-06","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many civil servants in his Department are paid through limited companies.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","39396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522998","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-14","<p>The published Cabinet Office Annual Report and Accounts (ARA) contains both the proportion of staff in the Department for Culture, Media and Sport that are (a) payroll and (b) non-payroll staff and the associated spend. The ARA for each financial year from 2010-11 to 2014-15 are available on <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">gov.uk</a>.</p><p>The 2015-16 data will be published in due course.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","39378","2016-06-14T15:09:24.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522998/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522998/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522998/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-06","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how much was spent on non-payroll staff in his Department in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","39465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522999","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-14","<p>The Government fully recognises the importance of the food and drinks sector to our economy, and appreciates that there is a creative element to work in this sector. The definition of the Creative Industries since 2013 has been based on a Creative Intensity approach, which measures the proportion of jobs within an industry that are classified as creative. The proportion of these jobs in the 'food and drink' industry was below the 30 per cent threshold set in 2013, and was therefore not included in the Creative Industries Economic Estimates.</p><p>Earlier this year, this Department carried out a consultation on our Economic Estimates for the Creative Industries, which included asking whether we should review the sectors included within the Creative Industries based on the existing Creative Intensity approach. We published our response to this consultation on 9 June, which stated that we will continue to review the Creative Intensities on an on-going basis to ensure they remain relevant. The Standard Occupational Classifications (SOC) which underpin this work are currently being reviewed, however, and we will wait for the outcome of that review before deciding whether and when to make any changes to the occupations which contribute to the Creative Industries.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-06-14T10:53:43.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522999/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522999/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522999/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-06","Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, for what reasons the food and drink industry does not meet his Department's criteria for inclusion on its list of creative industries.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","39414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523000","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-13","<p>The amount spent on non-payroll staff in 2015-16 is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-06-13T15:06:59.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523000/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523000/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523000/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-06","Ministry of Defence: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much was spent on non-payroll staff in his Department in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","39466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523001","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-13","<p>No civil servants employed by the Ministry of Defence are paid through limited companies.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-06-13T15:07:33.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523001/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523001/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523001/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-06","Ministry of Defence: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many civil servants in his Department are paid through limited companies.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","39397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523002","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-13","<p>The table below shows the number of payroll and non-payroll appointments made by the Ministry of Defence (MOD) in each of the last six Financial Years (FY).</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>FY</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Payroll staff</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Non-Payroll staff</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>66,187</p></td><td><p>1,571</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>62,736</p></td><td><p>1,701</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>54,973</p></td><td><p>1,764</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>52,992</p></td><td><p>3,440</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>52,278</p></td><td><p>3,739</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>52,295</p></td><td><p>3,646</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Off-payroll workers play an important role in helping the MOD meet short term needs for specialist advice and interim service.</p><p> </p><p>Information about the MOD’s senior payroll appointees engaged for over £220 a day for more than six months, and those of its Arm’s Length Bodies have been published in the relevant Annual Reports and Accounts since FY 2012-13.</p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-06-13T15:23:12.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523002/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523002/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523002/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-06","Ministry of Defence: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what proportion of staff in his Department were (a) payroll and (b) non-payroll staff in each financial year from 2010-11 to 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","39379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523003","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-13","<p>The loading and unloading of freight from Ministry of Defence chartered vessels is conducted by the Ascension Island Government. A Health and Safety and Environmental Risk Assessment of loading/unloading equipment at the Ascension Islands pier head was undertaken by the Joint Forces Command Health and Safety lead in September 2015.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","39958","2016-06-13T16:21:26.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523003/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523003/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523003/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-06","Ascension Island: Piers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment his Department has conducted of whether military personnel and contractors are able safely to load and unload equipment from Ministry of Defence vessels onto the pier head at Ascension Island.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","39460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523004","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-09","<p>The proportion of the defence procurement budget, and the defence budget spent on foreign military sales in each financial year cannot be provided. Under the Foreign Military Sales Agreement (FMS), Her Majesty's Government commits to FMS cases with the US Government which then places contracts with industry to deliver our requirements. Additionally, FMS cases typically cover differing periods of performance, thereby making estimation of the commitment that would fall within each financial year unreliable.</p><p> </p><p>The number of new cases, together with their values, committed to under FMS for each financial year is given in the table below. They do not equate to actual expenditure, accruals or contractual commitments and include contingency provisions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>No. of new cases</p></td><td><p>Value of new cases ($millions)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>22</p></td><td><p>995</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>30</p></td><td><p>111</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>33</p></td><td><p>284</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>23</p></td><td><p>137</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>25</p></td><td><p>301</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>26</p></td><td><p>328</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>32</p></td><td><p>245</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17 to date</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>13</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Totals</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>197</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2,414</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","39499 ; 39500","2016-06-09T15:19:47.583Z",,"http