"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523140","Department for Transport","false","2016-06-14","<p>The final figure will be published in the Department’s 2015/16 Annual Report and Accounts in due course.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-06-14T12:07:27.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523140/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523140/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523140/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-06","Department for Transport: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much was spent on non-payroll staff in his Department in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","39477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523141","Department for Transport","false","2016-06-09","<p>There is no available data on the historical level of funding allocated specifically to the Incident Support Unit service in the geographical operational area for trunk roads motorways in the North West, where the M56 Motorway is located.</p><p> </p><p>This Incident Support Unit was provided to Highways England’s predecessor organisation, the Highways Agency, by a contractor until 2012. There was a lump sum payment for various duties and it is not possible to disaggregate the cost of the Incident Support Unit service from the overall payments.</p><p> </p><p>A new Asset Support Contract replaced the previous approach in November 2012, and this no longer requires the contractor to provide a dedicated Incident Support Unit team. Incident response is now handled by the trained operatives in the general workforce, who are already working on the road network. This has proved to be a more flexible and cost-effective way of managing incidents.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-06-09T12:16:19.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523141/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523141/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523141/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-06","M56","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what level of funding was allocated to Department for Transport Incident Support Units serving the M56 between junctions 12 and 14 in each of the last 10 years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","39491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523142","Department for Transport","false","2016-06-13","<p>The Government remains committed to supporting the UK’s zero emission motorcycle industry. We have been working with stakeholders on the details of the most suitable scheme and will make a further announcement shortly.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-06-13T12:11:56.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523142/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523142/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523142/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-06","Electric Vehicles: Motorcycles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to his Department's press release of 27 March 2015, Government revs up motorcycle market, if he will implement grants for the purchase of electronic motorcycles.","false","Biography information for Chris Law","Dundee West","Chris Law","39421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523143","Department for Transport","false","2016-06-09","<p>Analysis is being undertaken on future levels of passenger demand at Coventry for the West Midlands franchise competition to prepare for the Invitation to Tender, as well as for the InterCity West Coast franchise.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-06-09T10:25:57.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523143/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523143/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523143/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-06","Railways: Coventry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 26 May 2016 to Question 37977, what estimate his Department has made of future levels of passenger travel (a) to and (b) from Coventry railway station in each of the next 10 years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","39483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523144","Department for Transport","false","2016-06-09","<p>Work is currently in progress assessing trends on the routes from and to Coventry as part of the West Midlands and InterCity West Coast franchise competitions. The Invitation to Tender for the West Midlands franchise is due to be released shortly.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-06-09T10:22:50.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523144/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523144/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523144/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-06","Railways: Coventry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 26 May 2016 to Question 37977, what comparative assessment he has made of trends in the number of passengers travelling from and to (a) Coventry railway station and (b) other stations in the UK; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","39485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523145","Department for Transport","false","2016-06-09","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency acknowledges that waiting times at Hull are unacceptable and that this test centre is in need of additional resource and there will be three extra examiners going into this test centre over coming months. This and new contractual overtime rates will reduce waiting times at Hull.</p><p><em> </em></p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-06-09T13:10:18.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523145/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523145/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523145/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-06","Driving Tests: Kingston upon Hull","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make it his policy to increase the number of driving test inspectors based at the Hull testing site so as to ensure a driving test at that site can be booked within one month.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","39366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523146","Department for Transport","false","2016-06-09","<p>The main cause of current waiting times across the country is a significant and sustained surge in demand for driving tests, the last time we saw demand at such high levels was in 2005/6.</p><p> </p><p>The average waits for a driving test appointment in (a) England and (b) at Hull test centre are as follows:</p><p> </p><p><strong>England </strong></p><p>Car – 12 weeks</p><p>Taxi – eight weeks</p><p>Module one motorcycle test – six weeks</p><p>Module two motorcycle test – six weeks</p><p> </p><p><strong>Hull driving test centre</strong></p><p>Car – 15 weeks</p><p>Taxi – nine weeks</p><p>Module one motorcycle test – 11 weeks</p><p>Module two motorcycle test – one week</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Our 2015/16 recruitment campaigns resulted in 193 new examiners starting work at test centres across Britain. A further 48 examiners have started testing since April 2016, and we have made employment offers to an additional 110 people, who are currently either attending the new entrant training course, or waiting to attend one.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-06-09T13:14:09.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523146/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523146/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523146/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-06","Driving Tests","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the average wait is for a driving test appointment (a) in England and (b) at the Hull test centre.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","39367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523147","Wales Office","false","2016-06-13","<p>The Wales Office spent £56,561 on non-payroll staff in 2015-16.</p><p> </p><p>In 2015-16, the Department used non-payroll (agency) staff to cover for staff on maternity leave and for vacant posts.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2016-06-13T14:27:12.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523147/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523147/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523147/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-06-06","Wales Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how much was spent on non-payroll staff in his Department in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","39479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523148","Wales Office","false","2016-06-13","<p>The payroll information requested is shown below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total Staff</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>(a) </strong><strong>Payroll Staff Percentage</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>(b) </strong><strong>Non-Payroll Staff Percentage</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010/11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>57</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>96%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>4%</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>55</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>98%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2%</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>53</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>98%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2%</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>50</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>92%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>8%</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>49</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>88%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>12%</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2015/16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>44</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>95%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>5%</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The non-payroll staff are those contracted through an agency.</p><p> </p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2016-06-13T14:28:38.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523148/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523148/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523148/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-06-06","Wales Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what proportion of staff in his Department were (a) payroll and (b) non-payroll staff in each financial year from 2010-11 to 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","39392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523149","Attorney General","false","2016-06-09","<p>Offences of using poison or instruments to cause miscarriage and supplying or procuring poison or instruments to cause miscarriage (sections 58 and 59 Offences Against the Persons Act 1861) are usually investigated by the police and, in England and Wales, prosecuted by the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS).</p><p>The CPS will only bring or continue with a prosecution where both stages of the test set down in the Code for Crown Prosecutors are met, i.e. that there is sufficient evidence to provide a realistic prospect of conviction and, if so, that a prosecution is required in the public interest.</p><p>In England and Wales, section 1 of the Abortion Act 1967 provides a defence to a prosecution under sections 58 or 59 where a pregnancy is terminated by a registered medical practitioner in accordance with the provisions of the Abortion Act 1967.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2016-06-09T11:12:28.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523149/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523149/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523149/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-06-06","Abortion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what his policy is on the prosecution of women who seek a medical abortion under the Offences Against the Person Act 1861.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","39290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523150","Women and Equalities","false","2016-06-14","<p>The Coalition Government’s Women’s Engagement Programme engaged women in dialogue with government through a range of means including ministerial roundtables, consultation events, social media, an online newsletter and a four nations ministerial roadshow. We are currently considering options for building on this work and how we can effectively engage with women whose voices are less often heard. I also refer the MP for Lancaster and Fleetwood to the answer to PQ <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-04-20/34907/" target="_blank">34907</a>, which sets out the Ministers for Women and Equalities' recent engagement with women’s organisations.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-06-14T14:30:31.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523150/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523150/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523150/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-06-06","Politics and Government: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what progress the Government has made on its women's engagement programme.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","39325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523151","Women and Equalities","false","2016-06-14","<p>I greatly value the expertise of women’s civil society and the Secretary of State for Education and Minister for Women and Equalities and I have met with many representatives since taking on our current roles. My officials also frequently consult the women’s sector on policy issues, including policy development, to ensure we benefit from the knowledge and understanding of relevant experts – for example on issues such as the gender pay gap, flexible working and gender diversity of company boards.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-06-14T14:35:06.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523151/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523151/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523151/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-06-06","Third Sector: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what steps she has taken to implement the Government's policy on increasing the involvement of women's civil society in the development of government policy.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","39326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523152","Women and Equalities","false","2016-06-14","<p>The Government remains committed to gender equality. When appropriate we fund women’s organisations to carry out activities that further this aim. The criteria we use to determine which organisations to fund vary according to the policy aims that we are seeking to achieve.</p><p>Some of the most significant funding streams for UK women’s organisations in the last three years have come from HM Treasury, the Home Office and the Department for Communities and Local Government. HM Treasury has used £15 million collected from VAT on sanitary products to fund women’s charities – the grantees were announced in March 2016. The Department for Communities and Local Government also made available £250,000 to community and voluntary sector organisations as part of its Women’s Empowerment Fund in 2015-16 and continues to provide funding for refuges. Furthermore, the Home Office is providing funding to organisations and refuges supporting female victims of domestic and other forms of violence, as announced in the refreshed cross-Government strategy to tackle Violence Against Women and Girls on 8 March 2016.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-06-14T14:25:23.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523152/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523152/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523152/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-06-06","Voluntary Organisations: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what criteria the Government uses in deciding which women's organisations to fund; how much funding the Government gave to women's organisations in each of the last three years; and which such organisations received funding from government in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","39327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523153","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-06-14","<p>The information is provided in the following table:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Proportion of payroll staff (%) </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Proportion of non-payroll staff (%)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>99.4</p></td><td><p>0.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>99.7</p></td><td><p>0.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>99.9</p></td><td><p>0.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>99.9</p></td><td><p>0.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>99.9</p></td><td><p>0.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>99.9</p></td><td><p>0.1</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Of the 520 non-payroll staff in the latest year the majority were employed to develop the technology for our major welfare reforms.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-06-14T10:32:19.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523153/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523153/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523153/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-06-06","Department for Work and Pensions: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of staff in his Department were (a) payroll and (b) non-payroll staff in each financial year from 2010-11 to 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","39393"
