"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522518","Department for Education","false","2016-06-08","<p>The response to Question 35933 stated that the consultation in 2013 was an important exercise to seek views on aspects of policy. An answer to that question does not, therefore, appear anywhere in the consultation.</p><p> </p><p>We work with teachers and head teachers as a matter of course. This included the 2013 primary assessment and accountability consultation.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-06-08T16:32:11.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522518/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522518/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522518/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-06-03","Primary Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the Answer of 5 May 2016 to Question 35933, on primary education, where the proportion of the teachers and head teachers who supported the principle of the assessment reforms when responding to the 2013 consultation appears in the analysis of consultation responses.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","39094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522519","Department for Education","false","2016-06-13","<p>The Department is consulting on key elements of the operation and delivery of the 30 hour extended free entitlement. This includes how the entitlement will be delivered, and how it will meet and be responsive to the needs of working parents. To date we have received over 1000 responses from a wide range of childcare providers, local authorities and provider organisations. We will use these views to inform our thinking as we move to delivering the 30 hours policy. The consultation is available at: <a href="https://consult.education.gov.uk/early-years-funding/childcare-free-entitlement" target="_blank">https://consult.education.gov.uk/early-years-funding/childcare-free-entitlement</a></p><p> </p><p>We know there are historical inconsistencies and inefficiencies with the current funding system for 3- and 4-year-olds. That is why we will introduce a national funding formula for early years so that funding is transparently and fairly matched to need and fairly distributed between different types of providers and different parts of the country.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","39056","2016-06-13T14:41:33.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522519/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522519/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522519/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-06-03","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what representations she has received from local authorities on the ability of those authorities to fund an increase in free childcare entitlement to 30 hours per week.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","39057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522520","Department for Education","false","2016-06-13","<p>We are currently commissioning the evaluation of early implementation of 30 hours free childcare. An invitation to tender was published in May 2016 with a view to awarding the contract to a successful bidder by the end of June 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The evaluation will focus on generating learning that can be used by Early Implementers and all local councils ahead of national implementation in September 2017.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-06-13T14:42:59.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522520/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522520/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522520/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-06-03","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to evaluate the pilot schemes on increasing free childcare entitlement to 30 hours per week.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","39054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522521","Department for Education","false","2016-06-13","<p>The government conducted a 6 month long review of the cost of childcare provision in 2015 - the most in depth analysis of this market we have ever had, and was described by the National Audit Office as “thorough and wide-ranging”. This assessed the costs of different types of providers across the country, including nurseries in deprived areas. The review is available online at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/review-of-childcare-costs" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/review-of-childcare-costs</a></p><p> </p><p>Based on this information we announced at the 2015 Spending Review that the government would provide £300 million per year for a significant uplift to the average funding rates paid for the 2-, 3- and 4-year-old entitlements from 2017-18. Together with the funding announced at last summer’s Budget, we will be investing over £1 billion more per year by 2019-20 to fund our commitments on the entitlements.</p><p> </p><p>We will also be introducing a national funding formula for the early years so that funding is transparently and fairly matched to need and fairly distributed between different types of providers and different parts of the country. We will be consulting on detailed proposals later this year.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-06-13T14:39:12.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522521/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522521/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522521/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-06-03","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the potential financial effect on nurseries in deprived areas of her plans to increase the free childcare entitlement to 30 hours per week.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","39058"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522522","Department for Education","false","2016-06-13","<p>In 2014/15 [1], there were 194,908 entries in England and 1,616 entries in Wiltshire for GCSE design and technology [2],[3].</p><p> </p><p>[1] Information is based on final 2014/15 figures.</p><p>[2] GCSE design and technology includes D&amp;T Electronic Products, D&amp;T Food Technology, D&amp;T Graphic Products, D&amp;T Product Design, D&amp;T Resistant Materials, D&amp;T Systems &amp; Control, D&amp;T Textiles Technology, Graphics, Motor Vehicle Studies, D&amp;T Engineering.</p><p>[3] Revised 2014/15 Information on the number of entries for GCSE technology and design is published in the “Revised GCSE and equivalent results in England: 2014 to 2015” statistical first release at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/493476/SFR01_2016_Subject_Tables.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/493476/SFR01_2016_Subject_Tables.xlsx</a> (Table S5)</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-06-13T16:00:39.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522522/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522522/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522522/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-06-03","Design and Technology: GCSE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many pupils studied GCSE design and technology in (a) England and (b) Wiltshire in the last year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","39154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522523","Department for Education","false","2016-07-01","<p>Design and Technology is a subject that can inspire and equip young people for further study and careers in a range of design and engineering fields. Our reform ensures the Design and Technology curriculum and qualifications are aligned with industry practice. The new GCSE and A levels move the subject on from its craft-based roots into a high-tech qualification.</p><p>The EBacc has been designed to be limited in its size in order to provide a rigorous academic core whilst leaving space in the curriculum for pupils to study other subjects of their choice. On average, pupils in state-funded schools enter nine GCSEs and equivalent qualifications, rising to more than ten for some pupils. As the EBacc covers up to eight GCSEs, this leaves room for other choices, including Design and Technology.</p><p>On 3 November 2015, the Secretary of State for Education launched a public consultation seeking views on the government’s proposals for the implementation of the EBacc. The consultation closed on 29 January 2016 and the Government’s response will be published in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-07-01T13:52:05.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522523/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522523/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522523/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-06-03","Design and Technology: English Baccalaureate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the potential merits of including design and technology in the EBacc.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","39157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522524","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-08","<p>The Department has received the Committee on Climate Change report. We are considering the report and will lay it before Parliament with our response in due course.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-08T14:27:26.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522524/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522524/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522524/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-03","Oil: Exploration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if she will lay before Parliament (a) the Committee on Climate Change report on the compatibility of UK onshore petroleum with meeting UK carbon budgets and (b) her response to that report before 14 June 2016.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","39080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522525","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-13","<p>DECC Ministers have approved the following public appointments since May 2015 (see attached).</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-13T16:00:38.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522525/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522525/answer","Question 39040 - Public appointments by DECC Ministers Since May 2015.docx","Question 39040 - Public appointments by DECC Ministers Since May 2015.docx","Public appointments by DECC Ministers May 2015-","Public appointments by DECC Ministers May 2015-","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522525/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-03","Department for Energy and Climate Change: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, which public appointments (a) she and (b) Ministers of her Department have approved since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","39040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522526","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-08","<p>We are aiming to consult on the next phase of the Energy Company Obligation as soon as we can. We recognise the interest in understanding the detail of the Obligation from April 2017 and some aspects have already been made known, including the scale and the increased focus on those most in need. The Department meets regularly with a broad range of stakeholders and exchanges learning on the operation of the current Obligation as well as thinking on possible future design.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-08T16:11:42.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522526/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522526/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522526/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-03","Energy Company Obligation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if she will set out a timeline for consulting on the Energy Company Obligation.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","39093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522527","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-08","<p>In the Department of Energy and Climate Change there were 193 contingent staff paid off-payroll in the period from May 2015 to 30 April 2016. Not all contingent staff were in post for the full 12 months.</p><p> </p><p>Contingent staff are engaged to undertake short term activities to meet business needs.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-08T16:41:12.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522527/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522527/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522527/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-03","Department for Energy and Climate Change: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many staff of her Department have been paid off-payroll since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","39039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522528","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-08","<p>Interoperability is one of the Government’s key requirements for the main installation stage of smart metering, which is due to commence later this year. The Government has already established common technical standards for the smart metering equipment (SMETS) and put in place the Data and Communications Company (DCC). This is responsible for setting up the nationwide communications infrastructure across Great Britain to send and receive information from any energy supplier to smart meters.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-08T16:43:16.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522528/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522528/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522528/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-03","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what her policy is on making smart meters universally compatible for all energy suppliers.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","39050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522529","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-08","<p>DECC ministers and officials engage regularly with Ofgem, both bilaterally and as part of the Programme’s Transitional Governance Model arrangements, in line with our roles set out in the joint DECC/Ofgem open letter to the industry on the implementation of smart metering published in December 2014:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-implementation-and-regulation-of-smart-metering-a-joint-deccofgem-open-letter-to-the-industry" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-implementation-and-regulation-of-smart-metering-a-joint-deccofgem-open-letter-to-the-industry</a>.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-08T16:39:24.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522529/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522529/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522529/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-03","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what recent discussions she has had with Ofgem on the roll out of smart meters to homes across the UK.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","39051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522530","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-08","<p>The Department has continued to engage and meet with both bidders in the carbon capture and storage (CCS) competition – Shell and Capture Power Limited. We are clear that CCS is too expensive and costs must come down. We continue to work with wider industry to help develop CCS cost efficiency in the UK, including through the joint Government-industry CCS Development Forum, which I co-chair</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-08T16:09:39.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522530/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522530/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522530/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-03","Carbon Capture and Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps she has taken to engage with the bidders for the carbon capture and storage competition since its cancellation.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","39014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522531","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-08","<p>Since the cancellation of the Carbon Capture and Storage (CCS) Competition, the Department has made the following payments to the bidders under the terms of the Front End Engineering and Design contracts between Government and each bidder:</p><p> </p><p>White Rose Project</p><p>Capture Power Ltd: £26,377,223.86</p><p>Peterhead Project</p><p>Shell: £3,032,394</p><p>SSE: £0.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-08T16:10:20.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522531/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522531/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522531/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-03","Carbon Capture and Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what payments her Department has made to (a) White Rose CCS, (b) Shell and (c) SSE since the cancellation of the carbon capture and storage competition.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","39015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522532","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-08","<p>The carbon capture and storage competition document stated that the Department would not meet bidders’ costs other than those shared with the Department through the Front End Engineering and Design (FEED) contract, and that payments to bidders since November 2015 have been consistent with the terms and conditions in those FEED contracts agreed between Government and each bidder.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-08T16:11:02.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522532/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522532/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522532/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-03","Carbon Capture and Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether the bidders for the carbon capture and storage competition have (a) sought and (b) been offered compensation from her Department for costs they incurred prior to that competition's cancellation.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","39016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522533","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-08","<p>Expenditure on contingent workers is published each year in the Annual Report and Accounts. The expenditure for the past five years is in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2010-11 £’000</p></td><td><p>2011-12 £’000</p></td><td><p>2012-13 £’000</p></td><td><p>2013-14 £’000</p></td><td><p>2014-15 £’000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Contingent Workers</p></td><td><p>4,890</p></td><td><p>3,420</p></td><td><p>4,511</p></td><td><p>6,877</p></td><td><p>6,245</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-08T16:40:06.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522533/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522533/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522533/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-03","Department for Energy and Climate Change: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how much her Department has spent on agency workers in each of the last five financial years.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","39232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522534","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-13","<p>As at 30 April 2016 (a) 50% of permanent Core DECC staff were female and (b) 13% were from an ethnic minority.</p><p> </p><p>The percentage of staff in (b) is of those who have declared their ethnicity.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-13T15:42:07.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522534/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522534/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522534/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-03","Department for Energy and Climate Change: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what proportion of civil servants in her Department are (a) female and (b) from an ethnic minority.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","39231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522535","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-08","<p>This is a matter for individual coal generating companies.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-08T16:08:52.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522535/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522535/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522535/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-03","Coal: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what information her Department holds on plans by UK companies or organisations to export coal held in UK stockpiles.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","39230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522536","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-08","<p>The Department of Energy and Climate change has one executive agency, the Oil and Gas Authority. There were 21 contingent staff paid off-payroll in the period from May 2015 to 30 April 2016. Not all contingent staff were in post for the full 12 months.</p><p> </p><p>Contingent staff are engaged to undertake short term activities to meet business needs.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-08T16:40:40.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522536/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522536/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522536/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-03","Department for Energy and Climate Change: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many staff in agencies for which she is responsible have been paid off-payroll since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","39233"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522537","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-06-08","<p>Defra does not keep records of noise nuisance incidents. Local authorities are the main enforcers of the statutory noise nuisance regime and associated legislation. There is no obligation on local authorities to report noise complaints data to central government. The Chartered Institute of Environmental Health carries out a voluntary annual survey of local authorities regarding complaints about noise, the results of which are published as part of the Public Health Outcomes Framework and may be found via the following weblink: <a href="http://www.phoutcomes.info/search/noise" target="_blank">http://www.phoutcomes.info/search/noise</a>.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-06-08T15:47:25.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522537/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522537/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/522537/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-06-03","Noise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what measures her Department has in place to record noise nuisance incidents.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","39265"
